In [4]:
number_of_triangles = sum(triangles.values()) / 3
print(number_of_triangles)

34220.0

The anonymized high school interaction data attempts to determine the number of interactions high school students at a fictitious educational institute socially connect with one another on a daily basis. Specifically, this data seeks to find how many trios, or groups of 3 students, regularly associate with one another. These trios are represented as triangles in the network. By using a sum function, I was able to determine that this high school had 34,220 trios. In relation to the network, this is a small number. This is because the number of possible (hypothetical) trios is over 5.7 million.

Diving deeper into the data, the average clustering coefficient seeks to determine the number of interactions that an individual students neighbors interact with one another. By using the average clustering coefficient function from the networkx library, I was able to determine that on average, a node will have a clustering coefficient over just over 0.5. In other words, this means that there is a 50/50 chance that students neighbors will interact with one another. These measures tell me that the network consists of a symmetrical balance between nodes and their edges that (when removed) disconnect the network and nodes and their edges that also (when removed) do not disconnect the network.

Note: An example of a local bridge is as follows: ('source', 'target', span). In this case, all bridges have a span length of 3.

A bridge represents an edge that (when removed) disconnects the graph. In this network, there are no bridges. This is because every node has a degree greater than one. However, there are 65 local bridges which represent edges between two students that have no common neighbors. It means that this network illustrates a large, singular group of students that know each other very well. Finally, every local bridge has a span of 3. In terms of social community, this means that for every individual student, you can connect individual students by no more than two common unique neighbors.

In [17]:
def neighborhood_overlap(g, u, v):
    n_common_nbrs = len(set(nx.common_neighbors(g, u, v)))
    n_join_nbrs = g.degree(u) + g.degree(v) - n_common_nbrs - 2
    return n_common_nbrs / n_join_nbrs

After calculating neighborhood overlap for every edge in the network and recreating a graph via a regression plot, there appears to be no correlation between an edges weight and neighborhood overlap. This is because most edges have a low weight value but varying neighborhood overlap values. This means that there is a wide range of common relationships between two people. For example, one pair of students may share very few common neighbors; whereas another pair of students may share a large number of common neighbors, in relationship to the total number of edges in the network.
